<HEADLINE>
FT  02 OCT 92 / World Trade News: Telecom giants to share network
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HUGO DIXON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SIX OF the world's largest international telecommunications carriers
yesterday announced an agreement to pool parts of their submarine cable
capacity to create a shared global network.
The carriers said the new network, which will be ready by the end of next
year, would provide them with a more flexible and cost-effective way of
routing telecommunications traffic around the world than the current system
of bilateral arrangements.
It would, for example, allow them to respond more quickly to disasters such
as earthquakes, and provide customers with services at shorter notice.
The six carriers are American Telephone &amp; Telegraph, British
Telecommunications (BT), France Telecom, Germany's Deutsche Telekom, Japan's
Kokusai Denshin Denwa, and Australia's OTC.
BT stressed yesterday that the agreement had 'no regulatory implications'
and was therefore not being registered with authorities such as the European
Commission.
It was a co-operation agreement, not a joint venture, it said.
Each carrier would continue to own the capacity it put into the global
network and the financial arrangements under which each carrier gained
access to another operator's infrastructure would be exactly the same as at
the moment, BT said.
Another 14 or 15 carriers could later join the project called the Global
Network Project, which could end up 'spanning the whole world', BT said.
</TEXT>
