<HEADLINE>
FT  02 OCT 92 / Italy seeks EC loan to boost lira: Rome begins talks with
partners on L10,000bn stand-by loan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM and LIONEL BARBER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ROME, BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Italian government yesterday said it had begun discussions with its EC
partners on a special stand-by loan to boost the lira and sustain confidence
in plans for an early return to the European Monetary System.
According to unofficial estimates last night, the loan could be the
equivalent of L10,000bn (Pounds 4.5bn).
The surprise move was announced along with Italy's 1993 budget which was
approved yeterday by the cabinet and promises to reform the country's
deteriorating public finances.
Prof Giuliano Amato, the prime minister, said the aim of the loan was partly
political. At one level, he said Italy wished to demonstrate its continued
commitment to the EMS, but at the same time the loan appears designed to
provide a rigid external framework for Italy's economic performance. It
would make it more difficult for parliament to water down the budget.
Officials declined to reveal the amount of the loan but said it was
different from the UK's move earlier this month to go to the markets for an
Ecu loan to help protect sterling. It is expected to take up to four or five
weeks to negotiate and would not be drawn down until after the 1993 budget
was approved.
There was speculation yesterday that the stand-by facility might not be
fully used if granted, providing the currency markets stabilised and
interest rates began to fall. Mr Piero Barucci, the treasury minister, said
the facility would be a 'super-certification' by Italy's EC partners of the
country's credibility. The lira was still under pressure yesterday, hovering
around L880 to the D-Mark.
Officials in Brussels predicted a sympathetic response to the Italian loan
request. Mr Amato is viewed as the best hope for tackling the country's
budgetary crisis and restoring international confidence in the economy, but
he needs outside help, an EC official said.
An EC loan would support his efforts to win parliamentary approval for his
economic package, rather than a potentially contentious loan from the
International Monetary Fund. 'We would be keeping the problem within the
family,' the official said.
Brussels expects Mr Amato to seek financial aid under Rule 1969 adopted in
June 1988 allowing the EC to help countries which experience balance of
payments problems or adverse capital movements.
Some Ecu16bn (Pounds 12.59bn) has been set aside for support. Greece is the
only EC member to have applied, securing a Ecu2.2bn stabilisation loan in
February 1991, to prepare the country to join the next phase of monetary
union.
Under the deal, the Community goes to the capital markets to raise the money
on the best possible terms, using its own guarantees.
A maximum of Ecu14bn can be raised this way, with Ecu2bn or more coming as
medium term credits from member states.
Before 1988, Ireland, France and Italy all received European Community funds
to help them tackle balance of payments difficulties.
Italy's problems come amid the debate within the EC about the pros and cons
of a 'two-speed Europe.' In this sense, Brussels' support is viewed as an
important sign that all countries can at least aspire to monetary union, if
they take the necessary painful austerity measures.
</TEXT>
