FT  02 OCT 92 / Rouble's sharp fall continues
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN LLOYD
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Russian rouble dropped sharply again yesterday in interbank trading in
Moscow, from the previous record low of 254 to the new low of 309 to the
dollar.
The latest sharp fall means a drop in the rate for September of nearly
Rbs100 - from Rbs210.5 on September 1 to Rbs309 yesterday.
Mr Victor Gerashchenko, the Russian Central Bank chairman, told the Interfax
news agency that the issue of again fixing the rate of the rouble against
hard currencies would be 'most actively discussed' with the government in
the next month. He blamed expectations of a further rise in inflation
following higher fuel and energy prices for the continuing fall in the
rouble, and said the bank attempted only limited intervention.
The rouble fell yesterday as citizens were for the first time able to
collect vouchers with a face value of Rbs10,000 which will entitle them to
buy shares in companies soon to be offered for auction. The evidence from
Moscow was of a sluggish, almost reluctant response, with a fraction of
those planned for collecting their vouchers.
Perhaps symbolically, the first commercial bankruptcy in the former Soviet
Union was reported yesterday, in the county of Harju in Estonia. The
company, Norten, was declared bankrupt by the regional court and its assets
seized.
The September revolution, Page 22
