<HEADLINE>
FT  02 OCT 92 / Major set for battle with rebels
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN MAJOR last night set the stage for a bloody confrontation with his
party's Euro-sceptics by pledging to push ahead with ratification of the
Maastricht treaty.
In a determined move to re-establish his political authority without
splitting the Conservative party, Mr Major tempered his challenge to Tory
rebels by re-emphasising that sterling's re-entry to the European exchange
rate mechanism was on indefinite hold.
Senior ministers said it would be more than a year - and possibly as long as
two - before the pound was put back in the ERM. Mr Major is not ruling out
the possibility of tax increases next year if a tighter fiscal policy is
needed to underpin the government's anti-inflation strategy.
His clear response to charges that the government's European policy was
adrift came after a day in which a furious diplomatic row had been sparked
by the FT's publication of the Bundesbank's defence of its record during the
sterling crisis.
The prime minister said he wanted now to 'draw a line' under disputes with
Germany.
He rejected calls from Mr John Smith, the Labour leader, for the resignation
of Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, in the wake of the Bundesbank's
insistence it had met its obligations to defend sterling in the ERM.
Earlier the Foreign Office had summoned the German ambassador to receive a
formal protest against the embassy's decision to pass the statement to the
FT.
But after an 'expression of regret' by the Bundesbank over the incident, Mr
Major indicated that his priority was to re-establish good relations with
Bonn. That sentiment was echoed by Mr Klaus Kinkel, the German foreign
minister, who last night called for calm in Germany's relations with
Britain.
In visibly combative mood after securing cabinet agreement to reassert the
commitment to keep Britain at the 'heart of Europe', Mr Major said he wanted
a full-scale Commons debate on Maastricht after the Birmingham summit
scheduled for October 14.
Despite claims by the Euro-sceptics that he risks civil war on the Tory
backbenches, the prime minister indicated that the full force of the party
machine would be used to secure a majority for the legislation. He added:
'It is certainly the intention to pass the Maastricht Bill during this
session of parliament.' His high-risk decision to defy the Euro-sceptics -
for which he demand-ed and received the support of the cabinet - is designed
to fill the vacuum in foreign policy left by the ERM debacle. It aims to
rebut charges from friends as well as enemies that Mr Major has failed to
give a clear lead during the ensuing turmoil.
Last night, he left no doubt of his determination to get through the treaty
which he declared last December had represented 'game, set and match' for
Britain. 'I don't think that, upon reflection, the Commons will think it
appropriate for a British prime minister to negotiate a bill, agree a bill
and then abandon it - and I don't propose to do so,' he said.
That comment came after he had told colleagues that unless Britain ratified
Maastricht it would never again be able to secure concessions in
negotiations with its European partners. He told the cabinet that nothing
less than 'the credibility of Britain' was at stake over the treaty.
Mr Major is aware that the move will provoke a series of damaging rows at
next week's Conservative party conference, where the Euro-sceptics are
promising to mobilise grass-roots opposition to Maastricht. But yesterday
Lady Thatcher indicated that she would not use a planned visit to the
Brighton conference to launch an attack on her successor in Downing Street.
The prime minister is optimistic of a deal with other EC leaders at
Birmingham on a declaration committing them to closer definition of the
division of authority between Brussels and national governments.
After an intense round of diplomatic contacts with his European partners
this week, Mr Major believes that a declaration embracing the so-called
subsidiarity principle will be one of several clarifications which will make
Maastricht more palatable both to Tory MPs and to Denmark, which voted
against Maastricht in a referendum, by the time of a second summit in
Edinburgh in December.
If the Birmingham meeting goes according to plan, Mr Major will hold a
debate on the principle of the Maastricht bill soon after the House of
Commons returns on October 19. Pressure will be applied to every Tory MP to
support it.
THE ANGLO-GERMAN ROW
