<HEADLINE>
FT  02 OCT 92 / Rift fears knock 5 pfennigs off sterling
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
STERLING dropped nearly five pfennigs against the D-Mark yesterday as
foreign exchange dealers were thrown into confusion by the new rift between
the UK Treasury and the Bundesbank.
The emergence of a new fault-line in Anglo-German relations pushed the pound
down to DM2.4770 in Asian trading on Wednesday night and the currency
bottomed out at DM2.4680 in Europe yesterday.
The pound later closed in London at DM2.4750, down 4 1/4 pfennigs on the day
and 16 per cent below its former central parity in the exchange rate
mechanism of DM2.95. Against the dollar, it closed down nearly 5 cents at
Dollars 1.7365.
In New York later, where the dollar was generally stronger, the pound
finished at DM4.7300 and Dollars 1.7405.
Dealers believe the immediate outlook for sterling and other European
currencies depends on whether the Bundesbank cuts interest rates at its
council meeting today.
Earlier this week, a member of the central bank's council said there would
be no German rate cut for six months. But a gradual reduction this week in
Bundesbank dealing rates in the German money market has fuelled new
optimism.
A number of leading participants in the foreign exchange market predicted
more sterling falls in the absence of a German rate cut and any
clarification of UK economic policy. 'Until this latest row, I had pencilled
in a low of DM2.40,' said one leading currency fund manager in London. 'But
colleagues now believe sterling could drop to DM2.30 unless a coherent UK
economic strategy materialises.'
The unrelieved strength of the D-Mark kept the Spanish peseta close to its
ERM floor and forced Spain's government to deny rumours of another
devaluation. The peseta closed against the D-Mark at Pta70.42, close to its
ERM floor of Pta72.62.
Sterling's weakness has triggered new fears of a devaluation of the Irish
punt, which hit a high of Pounds 1.055 yesterday.
Irish officials have said the punt should not strengthen above Pounds 1.05
because of the close trading relationship between the UK and Ireland.
