<HEADLINE>
FT  02 OCT 92 / UK Company News: Andrews Sykes' dissident calls for support
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JACQUES Murray, the dissident shareholder who holds a 26.6 per cent stake
in Andrews Sykes, the industrial services and environmental products group,
yesterday attacked the company's recent financial performance and called on
shareholders to support his bid to gain control of the board.
Andrews Sykes has set October 16 as the date for an extraordinary meeting
called at the request of Mr Murray who is demanding the removal of Mr David
Hubbard, chairman, and Mr David Crowe, a non-executive director, from the
5-man board and their replacement by himself and three of his associates.
In a letter to shareholders Mr Murray highlighted the 'repeated failure to
achieve expected levels of profitability' since 1989, and urged them to back
his resolutions.
Mr Murray, who holds his equity stake through two investment vehicles,
European Fire Protection Holding and Midland Bank Overseas Nominees, noted
that pre-tax profits had declined by 81 per cent since 1989, claimed that
profits have been 'shored up' by a pension fund surplus, and that dividends
have been paid from reserves in the past two years 'despite a clear need to
preserve resources.'
In an earlier letter Mr Hubbard strongly recommended shareholders to vote
against Mr Murray's resolutions, which he said was an 'unmerited and
unwelcome attempt to gain control of the company.'
</TEXT>
