<HEADLINE>
FT  01 OCT 92 / Management (Marketing and Advertising): Computer characters
champing at the bit - Gary Mead finds battle already joined in the Christmas
toy trade
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GARY MEAD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
October 1 - it must be time to start thinking about Christmas. At least,
that's the reasoning of manufacturers and retailers eager to grab a slice of
this year's estimated Pounds 1bn spending on gadgets, games and gizmos for
children.
Among those ready for take-off are the world's two leading producers of
electronic video games, Sega and Nintendo, both Japanese companies with a
global reach. Their march into the living rooms of the industrialised world
has strafed the traditional toy market and demolished a central icon of
American folksiness, the baseball bat.
According to Nintendo, electronic video games outnumber baseball bats in the
US. That warms the heart of Brian Moore, senior product manager at Bandai
UK, which markets Nintendo products in Britain; where the US has pioneered,
the UK will follow.
In the US and Japan, electronic video games have a 40 per cent household
penetration; that drops to just 14 per cent in the UK, though 50 per cent of
British homes with children have some form of electronic video game
installed. There is thus room for growth - and room for a mega-drive
marketing battle.
Peter Skinner, marketing manager of Hamleys, the London toy shop, says
electronic video games were 'the biggest selling toy item last Christmas and
we expect the same this year'.
Nintendo and Sega calculate the retail value of the UK market will be Pounds
500m this year - almost double that of 1991, and about half of all toy sales
 -from a standing start of just Pounds 20m in 1989.
Worldwide, Nintendo claims to have sold 615m items of games hardware in the
last six years, 10m of those in the UK. In the US, Nintendo claims the
retail value of its sales alone this year will be Dollars 4.8bn.
Nintendo claims an overall 80 per cent share of the international video
games market but clearly there is a marketing battle in progress over the
hearts and pockets of the world's children.
According to the UK magazine, Computer Trade Weekly, Sega dominates the
emerging and more technologically sophisticated 16-bit game console market
in the US, with a 61 per cent share, against Nintendo's 34 per cent. The
other 5 per cent is taken by NEC.
In the UK, Nintendo is spending Pounds 15m on marketing its three versions
of hand-held, 8-bit and 16-bit consoles which plug into ordinary television
sets.
Its rival, Sega, with its own versions of the same products, claims a UK
marketing budget of Pounds 19m this year, including a Pounds 2m sponsorship
deal during the summer of Independent Television's coverage of the European
football championship. By the end of this year, Sega will have spent about
Pounds 100m on marketing across Europe.
In the UK, the less expensive hand-held games market is dominated by
Nintendo, which has about 60 per cent market share, compared with Sega's 40
per cent.
The superior technology of the 16-bit consoles means they provide the
graphics and entertainment of arcade-style video games. Sega launched its
16-bit console in the UK two years ago - Nintendo came along earlier this
year - and Sega currently appears to be winning the battle.
According to one of London's leading toy retailers, 'Nintendo has not yet
got the word-of-mouth awareness that Sega has; last week we sold seven Sega
16-bit machines and two of Nintendo's'. Price is another factor; in the UK,
Sega's 16-bit machine retails at Pounds 129, against Nintendo's Pounds 180.
To capture the high ground in the UK, both companies are launching lavish
television advertising campaigns at the start of October; Nintendo has spent
Pounds 500,000 in production costs alone.
Part of Sega's strategy has been to take a leaf out of the Hollywood movie,
Big - where a teenager suddenly finds himself transformed into an adult, and
is recruited by a toy manufacturer as a product tester - by inviting
13-15-year-olds to attend its quarterly board meetings.
According to Philip Ley, marketing director of Sega Europe: 'Their role is
to discuss our plans for Sega, future product launches, the type of software
we should be launching, reaction to our promotions and TV advertising plans.
We also set them projects in between each board meeting; for instance, one
of them was how can we make Sega more appealing to women? They have a lot of
practical imput.'
But in the long-term, both Sega and Nintendo need to broaden their appeal.
Getting noticed by kids was the priority once - 'they are our best sales
people' says Brian Moore - but the new television advertising campaigns are
aimed at enticing the relatively untapped older teenage and adult markets.
Hence Sega's interest in event sponsorship. 'We wanted to leap-frog Nintendo
in terms of the way consumers, both dads and lads, perceived Sega as a
brand. In this market place - it's not the same everywhere - big is better.
We need to be seen as a big brand because kids tend to think if you are big,
you are going to have the best technology, the best games and the biggest
number of games. What we wanted to do in a very short space of time was to
catapult Sega into, for instance, the echelons of Coca-Cola,' says Ley.
There is nothing quite like a movie for generating interest in spin-off
products. But as part of its marketing strategy, Nintendo has taken the
unusual step of manufacturing the product first and producing the movie
second.
Nintendo claims that one of its characters, Super Mario, now has a
popularity rating in the US higher than that of Mickey Mouse. Sure enough,
Mario is to feature in a 1993 movie - The Super Mario Bros - played by the
character actor Bob Hoskins.
While market saturation is not yet on the horizon, the long-term future
dictates that both Sega and Nintendo must grow into new, demographically
older, markets. 'It is not so much that we fear market saturation as that we
wish to position Sega as a large credible brand, with a future not to remain
simply in the games consoles market but, over the next few years, to become
a home entertainment brand,' says Ley.
Moore supports the view that Nintendo's three hardware products require
different marketing: 'Initially, video games had a bad perception in
parents' minds. With (the hand-held) Game Boy, we took a softly-softly
approach, introduced consumer services, a free magazine and a telephone
hotline for problems. Our profile was young. Our structure for Super NES is
different, with a more street-credible approach, to go after an older
audience.'
But for the next three months, the battlefield is squarely sited on the
playground. And the big marketing spends have one simple end - get the brand
name noticed and win credibility.
According to David King, product manager of Virgin Games, one of the larger
retailers of electronic games, 'as far as kids are concerned, at the end of
the day it all comes down to something called 'street cred'. How do you get
that street cred? If you could bottle that, you'd make a million.'
