<HEADLINE>
FT  01 OCT 92 / Sale of privatised debt delayed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE UK government's plan to sell Pounds 1bn of debt owed it by privatised
companies has been delayed, though the government's advisers say they can
still complete the sale before the current financial year ends next April.
The disposal, part of the Treasury's plans to raise Pounds 8bn from
privatisations this year, had been due to proceed at the beginning of
October, when potential buyers were to register their interest.
However, Baring Brothers, which is advising the government, said it will not
invite buyers to come forward until it has had another 'two or three weeks'
to look into how the sale is handled.
Mr Simon Best, a Baring director, denied yesterday that the bank had hit
problems with the sale, or that it might completely revise the way the
disposal is handled. The extra time would allow Baring to look at possible
refinements to its plans, he said.
Baring said in August that it would hold two auctions, one for debt of BT
and one for the electricity companies. To stimulate competitive bids, only
the best Pounds 1bn of bids for the total debt, which has a current value of
around Pounds 4bn, will be accepted.
Electricity companies are the only ones allowed to bid for their own debt,
while BT will bid alongside third parties for its Pounds 1.69bn of debt
outstanding.
The main tax problem in the way of the privatised companies buying back
their own debt has already been resolved. The Treasury has agreed to allow
them to bid at a lower level, reflecting the fact that they will not be able
to claim any tax losses from buying back and cancelling debt which is
trading at a premium.
However, Baring is now considering refinements to the tax position. One
possibility would involve the debt being sold to specially-created companies
run by the privatised companies, allowing the debt to remain until its
normal maturity date and so getting around the tax problems of early
repayment.
Further complications have yet to be resolved on the accounting side. For
instance, the premium paid by companies which buy back their debt is likely
to be treated as a current expense in their accounts, reducing their
profits. A company which borrowed to refinance the debt, could get around
this accounting problem.
</TEXT>
