<HEADLINE>
FT  01 OCT 92 / Pound and lira come under fresh pressure
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE LIRA and sterling came under renewed pressure against the D-Mark
yesterday as tensions continued to dominate currency trading in and out of
the ERM.
The lira, which was suspended from the ERM two weeks ago, suffered a 5.8 per
cent fall against the D-Mark after investors became increasingly concerned
that the Bank of Italy would reintroduce exchange controls. The widespread
rumour that Italy was planning a partial freeze on bank accounts was
repeatedly denied by the Italian government and the Bank of Italy. This
could not stop the lira falling to a low of L900 from a previous close in
Europe of L847.6. It recovered to close in London at L876, while in New York
it finished at L867.35.
Markets remain concerned that Italy's emergency budget may have a difficult
passage through parliament.
The lira's difficulties triggered another fall for sterling, which touched a
historic low of DM2.50. Investors recalled that the last big run on the lira
was followed a day later by sterling's devaluation. The pound rallied to
close in London at DM2.5175, down  1/4 of a pfennig. In New York it closed
at DM2.5165.
Sterling's weakness was partly compounded by another fall in the dollar
against the D-Mark. Investors are increasingly concerned that the US
non-farm payroll figure for August, due out tomorrow, will be very weak.
The figure may trigger another cut in the US discount rate, widening the
differential between US and German interest rates. The dollar closed in
Europe at DM1.4135, after a low of DM1.4040. In New York it closed at
DM1.4113.
The D-Mark's renewed strength created another rise of tensions inside the
ERM, with the peseta and franc weakening.
Currencies, Page 37
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
