<HEADLINE>
FT  01 OCT 92 / International Company News: JP Morgan boycotts O&amp;Y meeting
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
JP MORGAN, the New York banking group, boycotted a creditors' meeting called
by Olympia &amp; York yesterday in protest against what the bank views as
totally inadequate proposals for restructuring the troubled property
developer's US debt.
Morgan's unhappiness with O&amp;Y's proposals is balanced, however, by its
willingness to put off for at least another month plans to seize an
interest-rate swap pledged as partial collateral on a USDollars 160m loan to
O&amp;Y.
The restructuring plan is designed to keep O&amp;Y's US operations out of the
bankruptcy protection sought last May for the parent company and its
Canadian subsidiaries, and for the Canary Wharf project in London.
O&amp;Y asked about 75 creditors who did attend the meeting in New York to defer
principal payments for about five years. It hopes to reach a comprehensive
agreement by the end of this year for a 'consensual long-term restructuring'
of the US debt.
Banking sources said that Morgan views the proposals as a 'complete
non-starter'. Morgan is the co-lead manager of the syndicate which advanced
the Dollars 160m loan. It has moved on several fronts in recent months to
secure its interests, including a threat to auction the swap and a demand
that it have greater control over the cash flow of several buildings also
pledged as security for the loan.
A JP Morgan spokesman said yesterday that 'constructive talks' were
continuing with O&amp;Y on the swap. The deadline for seizure has been extended
until October 29, at the earliest.
O&amp;Y's US subsidiary said its restructuring plan would enable it to maintain
its franchise as an owner and manager of properties concentrated in New York
City.
</TEXT>
