<HEADLINE>
FT  01 OCT 92 / UK Company News: Two companies' unusual approach to goodwill
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TWO QUOTED companies have adopted an unusual approach to new accounting
standards, according to Company Reporting, the Edinburgh-based monthly
monitoring service of annual accounts.
Enterprise Computer Holdings, the computing services company, and West
Trust, the fabrics manufacturer, have both been required to alter their
treatment of goodwill under a ruling issued last December by the urgent
issues task force of the Accounting Standards Board.
The ruling requires companies to reflect in their profit and loss account on
disposal any goodwill at the time of acquisition. Goodwill is the difference
between the net assets and the purchase price paid.
Both West Trust and Enterprise Computer include this goodwill element, but
split it between an adjustment of goodwill and a surplus or loss on sale and
closure of subsidiaries. They do not refer elsewhere in the accounts to the
full loss including goodwill.
West Trust shows a Pounds 2.3m goodwill item and a separate Pounds 480,000
loss on the sale of a subsidiary in its accounts for the year to March 31.
Enterprise Computer shows a Pounds 1.1m surplus on sale and a Pounds 23.1m
goodwill write-off as extraordinary items, and then reinstates the Pounds
23.1m below the line before showing a transfer from the profit and loss
account of Pounds 7m.
Mr Shaun Dowling, chairman of Enterprise Computer, says the company showed a
Pounds 1.1m surplus because it still held shares in the company it sold, and
separated out the two items because 'otherwise shareholders would have had a
heart attack to see the loss for the year without realising that no cash
went out.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
