<HEADLINE>
FT  01 OCT 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICIA MORISON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Just in time for Divali, the Hindu Festival of Lights, comes an absorbing
item on Down To Earth (8.00), C4's magazine programme on archaeology. The
Gundestrup Cauldron is the world's most famous cooking-pot. It has now
become the most enigmatic archaeological treasure ever unearthed in Denmark.
Archaeologists used to believe that this great silver cauldron of the 1st
century BC was Celtic.
Now they have wiped their spectacles and looked more closely. They discover
firstly that it was made in Romania and secondly that there are elephants on
the inside.
The controversial suggestion is that its makers were gypsies, the deities
are Hindu, and that Europe BC was blissfully multi-racial and multi-cultural
. . .
Which is emphatically not true of Kuwait, as the opening documentary of C4's
Critical Eye reminds us. Free Kuwait (9.00) goes over familiar terrain, the
Kuwaitis' dislike bordering on paranoid fear of the country's non-Kuwaiti
residents.
These are ingrained sentiments which, predictably perhaps, have not altered
one jot since the war.
