FT  01 OCT 92 / Letter: Oil companies' right to fear supermarkets
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr WILLIAM HODGSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, Guy de Jonquieres and Neil Buckley ('Supermarkets vie to fill up tanks
as well as trolleys: an increase in shopping around for petrol is worrying
oil companies', September 28) may have inadvertently misstated some
realities.
The average supermarket petrol site sells six times the volume of petrol
sold by a conventional petrol station. Petrol is a significant contributor
to profits for Sainsbury's and Tesco. In a price war between supermarkets
and oil companies, the former would win hands down. They are not burdened by
the oil companies' overheads.
It was no surprise to this company, which has produced a motorist's guide to
petrol, that an important oil company refused to co-operate with the
production of unbiased consumer information.
William Hodgson,
Seven Points Publications,
PO Box 119,
Chichester,
West Sussex PO18 9LY
