<HEADLINE>
FT  01 OCT 92 / EC pressure improves jobs rights
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CATHERINE MILTON and DAVID GARDNER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE government, under pressure from the European Commission, is to change
the law to give more employment rights to some public-sector workers.
The move follows the threat of legal action by the commission and will give
more legal protection to workers who lose their jobs or are re-hired on
worse terms when local-authority work is contracted out.
Under the 1981 British transfer regulations, passed to comply with an EC
directive, employers must honour the employment contracts they inherit when
they take over or merge with other commercial ventures. However, when
public-sector or other non-profit-making organisations change hands,
contracts are considered terminated.
The commission argues that the government is failing to enforce the
directive fully and has begun proceedings to take the UK to the European
court.
The government has now agreed to add an amendment to its planned employment
bill, due in the next parliamentary session, to extend the protection to all
workers.
The main effect is expected to be to benefit those employees who are
adversely affected by the contracting-out of local-government work under the
compulsory-tendering procedure. In some cases, companies have won contracts
under which they have recruited many of the council's existing workers for
lower pay, and others have been made redundant.
Councils have lost 38,414 jobs as a result of tendering since March 1987,
according to the Local Government Management Board. A further 2,000 jobs are
expected to be removed from direct employment by March.
The proposed law may deter some private contractors from bidding for
contracts. Companies have been attracted by the contracts partly because
they have been free to cut wage costs.
The proposed law will compel employers to consult representatives of the
workforce before any transfer of ownership or control. Employers do not have
to consult workers unless they recognise unions.
The government has agreed to strengthen the penalties employers face for
breaking the law. Employers found to have breached the present regulations
need pay only two weeks' wages in compensation.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
