<HEADLINE>
FT  01 OCT 92 / The Labour Party at Blackpool: Tradition meets the new
realism - The issues surrounding the future of the party's union links
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
YESTERDAY'S debate on the links between the party and its affiliated trade
unions was merely the public prelude to weeks of intense private debate.
Out of that private debate will come - probably in the new year - a report
on reforming the links, with huge implications for the party's finances,
membership, policy-making and, above all, its ethos and public image.
The trade unions provide just over half of Labour's financial resources and
from next year will cast 70 per cent of votes at the conference which,
supplemented by various policy forums, nominally decides policy.
Those 'block' votes are based on the 4.5m union members who do not contract
out of paying a political levy to the party with their union dues and who
dwarf the 260,000 individual members from the constituency parties.
Although links between unions and parties of the left are common throughout
the industrial world, the link in this country is one of the most intimate,
based on the fact that the unions founded the party and then with their
block votes succeeded in moderating the excesses of left-wing members.
Also, short of state funding for political parties or the creation of a
'mass' party - both highly improbable in the near future - Labour will
continue to need a lot of union cash if it is to compete effectively with
the Conservatives.
But critics of the links believe the party can now manage without the
unions' political presence. They believe affiliated unions are a sectional
interest group - representing less than a quarter of British workers - and,
especially in the south-east, helping to associate Labour with the past.
There has been no groundswell of support for a complete separation, and
union influence within the party is so entrenched that even shadow ministers
who might have led moves to divorce - such as Mr Tony Blair or Mr Gordon
Brown - have had to disguise their real views.
Some people even detect a slight retreat from the mildly reformist proposals
that the leaders of the big unions seemed ready to accept a few weeks ago,
such as complete withdrawal from the electoral college to elect the leader
and from the local block vote in constituency parties.
'We do not need a revolution, we do not need a divorce, we don't even need
separate beds,' says Mr John Edmonds, leader of the GMB general union, who
inadvertantly launched the post-election debate on union power in the party
through his television anointment of Mr John Smith as the new leader days
after the election defeat.
The make-up of the party's union link review body, where the private debate
will now take place, also rules out a radical break, although it may be
pushed slightly further than it wants to go by reformers in the shadow
cabinet.
Nonetheless, there is a wide consensus supporting the view that the links
must be made more democratically legitimate and that the corporate clout of
the unions, epitomised by the block vote, must be replaced with a new
relationship to individual levy-paying trade unionists.
Well over half of the 'phantom army' of the 4.5m levy payers vote Labour but
a large minority do not and yet their votes are still counted at Labour
conferences. At the heart of the review group's deliberations will be the
question of how to represent these levy payers more defensibly.
Several ideas are being canvassed. One of the most popular is to offer levy
payers full membership or possibly 'associate membership' of the party,
which would allow them to participate without any extra payment.
The obstacle to giving levy-paying members the same rights as ordinary
members is that the average levy payer contributes less than Pounds 2 a year
and individual members pay Pounds 15. If fees were harmonised, as proposed
by Mr Graham Allen MP, it would probably require a cut in the contribution
rate which might not be covered by extra members.
Drawing attention to the political levy might also cause more people to
exercise their right to 'opt out' or attract hostile attention from the
government.
How far will the review cut the union vote at conference - the most visible
manifestation of union power in the party?
Over the past five years the unions have spent less than half of the money
they raise through the levy on the Labour party. If the conference votes
were linked to the proportion of the party's costs that the unions now
cover, the union proportion of the vote would fall to just over 50 per cent.
The review body may cut the union vote to slightly below 50 per cent. But
the political trick, according to Mr Neil Stewart, a former adviser to Mr
Neil Kinnock, is to switch the flow of union cash to fund elections alone.
'The voters do not believe Labour can speak for the whole country if unions
provide its running costs but they do believe that general elections would
be unfair contests without union contributions,' he says.
Stewart does not believe that a mass party can be created by converting more
levy payers into members or by cutting membership fees (which will be
experimented with in a few constituencies). He points out that shop stewards
are the key to increased membership among union members and they are usually
keen to appear non-party so as not to alienate non-Labour voters.
Instead, if membership income and donations are to rise to cover more of the
party's costs, Stewart says the membership fee will have to go up to Pounds
30. That would confirm the fears of many Labour trade unionists that the
party is intent on cutting its links with the working class. The evidence of
yesterday's debate is that they have nothing to fear.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
