<HEADLINE>
FT  01 OCT 92 / The Labour Party at Blackpool: Floor revolts over pensions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE leadership suffered its first defeat of the conference yesterday when
delegates voted overwhelmingly to back a big rise in the state pension.
In a rare act of defiance, conference rejected a recommendation by the
national executive and supported increasing the state retirement pension for
a couple to a level equivalent to half average gross earnings in the UK.
Although embarrassing, the result does not commit Mr John Smith to adopting
the motion as official policy. Mr Donald Dewar, Labour's social security
spokesman, said he was 'not disconcerted' and that such a pension increase
was a reasonable long-term aspiration.
The motion agreed by conference also called for moves towards equality in
retirement ages to be achieved by reducing the normal retirement age for men
 -and not at the expense of women's entitlement. Labour's official policy is
to back a 'flexible decade' of retirement.
Delegates also wanted the introduction of pensions for all women, to be paid
from their 60th birthday, regardless of the age of their partner. Measures
were also proposed in the motion to protect pension funds from Maxwell-style
robberies.
Moving the motion, Mr Des Andrews, of the Usdaw shop-workers' union, accused
Mrs Margaret Thatcher, the former prime minister, of 'robbing' pensioners.
'The money that was taken, we want back at the earliest opportunity,' he
said.
'If any government tries to make our women work until they are 65 before
they get a pension, my union will be out on the streets, I can guarantee.'
Replying, Ms Brenda Etchells, an NEC member, said policies set out in the
motion pre-empted the results of the commission on social justice planned by
the party leadership. It could also result in overcompensating women
pensioners and discrimination against men.
But she launched an attack on the government's failure to support
pensioners, particularly in comparison with other European Community
countries.
</TEXT>
