<HEADLINE>
FT  01 OCT 92 / Rise in Scottish jobless forecast
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
UNEMPLOYMENT IN Scotland is likely to rise from 243,000 to a peak of 282,000
next year, then fall slowly fall back to 255,000 in 1996, according to a
monthly economic review published yesterday.
The Fraser of Allander Institute of Strathclyde University, Scotland's main
economic study organisation, said people could already expect to stay out of
work longer. It called for government measures to tackle the issue.
It said: 'The return of something like the former Community Programme is
urgently needed, especially in the urban and other areas where high and
persistent unemployment and long-term employment prevails.
'This would provide direction and purpose to those who presently have no
chance of participating in the formal labour market, and help avoid the
adverse social consequences of sustained job-lessness.'
It predicted that demand in the Scottish economy would rally in the second
half of this year, but recovery would not become strongly rooted until next
year.
The recent turmoil in the European exchange rate mechanism would stimulate
the real economy, but rising unemployment in July and August suggested that
any 'significant' upturn would not take place before next year, the
institute added.
</TEXT>
