<HEADLINE>
FT  01 OCT 92 / Burning midnight oil in case against auditors: The latest
leg of the battle to recover money for creditors
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE LIGHTS are burning late into the night in City offices this week as the
liquidators of the collapsed Bank of Credit and Commerce International
prepare the latest salvo in their attempt to recover money for creditors.
Lawyers and accountants have been working long hours putting the final
touches to a 'statement of claim' detailing charges likely to top Dollars
8bn (Pounds 4.6bn) against the two accountancy firms that were auditors to
BCCI in 1986.
Ernst &amp; Whinney - now part of Ernst &amp; Young - and Price Waterhouse were both
served with brief writs expressed in general terms last March. The
statements of claim shortly to arrive will go into far more detail.
Neither firm had received copies late yesterday, but under the court-agreed
timetable the statements were required to be lodged by the end of today.
They represent the next stage in a battle that will probably take at least
five years to reach the courts - if it makes it that far.
'These are vexatious actions with Mickey Mouse numbers on them,' said one
partner. Publicly, Ernst &amp; Young and Price Waterhouse were yesterday putting
a brave face on the allegations.
PW said: 'We are confident that the work of all of the PW people involved in
the BCCI audit was carried out to the highest professional standards.'
Both firms have said they intend to contest the legal action.
Ernst &amp; Young is also likely to argue that it was auditor to parts of BCCI
that were not the source of the fraud, and that it relied on the work of PW
as auditor to those which were.
PW has already spent more than Dollars 10m in legal fees to prepare a
defence. Ernst &amp; Young has spent about Pounds 1m. Some partners are
expressing private unease over the prospect of litigation that could make
them personally bankrupt.
The largest cases of claims for damages in which payments have been made
public include Pounds 50m against Arthur Young - now part of Ernst &amp; Whinney
 -in connection with Johnson Matthey Bankers in 1989, and Pounds 40m last
year from KPMG Peat Marwick in respect of Ferranti's acquisition of ISC.
When the big accountancy firms agree to a legal settlement, payment comes
from a variety of sources. The first few million dollars is paid directly
from the firm's own resources. Some may also be shared between international
partnerships.
External professional indemnity insurers will then provide cover for many
tens of millions more, although growing claims and sharply rising premiums
have made that cover increasingly difficult to obtain affordably in the last
few years.
In addition, the Big Six firms are all members of two secretive mutual
insurance companies based in Bermuda. One is called Pail (Professional
Assets Indemnity Ltd), and the other Padua (named after the Italian city for
some time credited as the birthplace of double-entry bookkeeping). These two
mutuals both plug certain 'gaps' in the cover offered by external insurers,
and extend it beyond the levels to which they are willing to underwrite
risk. That covers the firms up to about Dollars 110m.
The firms typically also have their own individual 'captive' insurers, which
might bring the total level of cover to about Dollars 150m. Beyond that, the
partners themselves - as the owners of the firms - are individually liable
up to the total value of their assets.
The firms emphasise that the likelihood of a settlement that would bankrupt
partners is infinitesimally small. They also hope that the government of Abu
Dhabi, the BCCI majority shareholder, will not want to risk scrutiny of its
role by bringing the matter to court.
But one professional involved in the preparation of the statement of claim
said: 'Brian Smouha would not bring a claim unless there were very serious
grounds for action.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
