<HEADLINE>
FT  01 OCT 92 / Clothing and engineering form industry lobby groups
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DANIEL GREEN and ANDREW TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EMPLOYERS in Britain's fragmented textiles and clothing industries are
joining forces from today in a new body, the British Apparel and Textiles
Confederation (BATC).
They want to raise their industries' lobbying power at a time when the
international trading agreements - General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade
and Multi-Fibre Arrangement - are being renegotiated.
Also in London yesterday an industrial pressure group aimed at reversing
almost 50 years of decline in Britain's manufacturing and engineering
industries was launched.
It is called the UK Industrial Group and it expects to draw its membership
from mainly small to medium-sized manufacturing companies.
The British Apparel and Textiles Confederation is the largest such
organisation in Europe, according to Mr John Wilson, its director-general.
Its size partly compensates for the fact that the textile and clothing
industry has shrunk under the weight of imports from low-cost countries.
Employment has fallen by about 25 per cent to 400,000 in the past decade.
BATC will advise employers on industrial relations, central pay bargaining
and marketing as well as lobbying.
The chairman is Mr James McAdam, who retired as deputy chairman and chief
executive of Coats Viyella last year.
BATC's creation is the culmination of a decade's work in reconciling
differences between such diverse groups as the British Throwster's
Association, whose 30-odd members help to process silk, and Coats Viyella,
Europe's biggest textiles manufacturer.
Twelve industry bodies whose roots can be traced back to the Industrial
Revolution are members of the BATC: the British Lace Federation; the British
Narrow Fabrics Association; the British Throwsters' Association; the Central
Council of the Irish Linen Industry; the Confederation of British Wool
Textiles; the Council of British Cotton Textiles; the Scottish Textile
Association; the Silk Association of Great Britain, the Textile Finishers
Association; the British Clothing Industry Association; the British Knitting
and Clothing Export Council and the Knitting Industries Federation.
Three companies become members in their own right: Coats Viyella, Courtaulds
Textiles and ICI Fibres.
The engineering body's 30 founding companies, forming the UK Industrial
Group, represent a variety of manufacturers from all over the country. The
group is launching a recruitment drive to increase the membership to 1,000
companies by the end of next year.
The group is to seek a meeting with Mr Michael Heseltine, the trade and
industry secretary. It is demanding the creation of a national economic
policy to foster closer co-operation between government, industry and the
City.
Mr David Turnbull, director-general of the new pressure group, said that in
the 1980s 'Mrs Thatcher saw off the unions but then left industry to sort it
out in a free-for-all which was fatal'.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
