<HEADLINE>
FT  01 OCT 92 / Orimulsion fuel fails environment test
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LASCELLES, Resources Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MOVES to introduce the controversial fuel orimulsion into Britain received a
setback yesterday when UK pollution inspectors indicated to National Power
that they would not approve it without further environmental measures.
National Power has been seeking permission to burn the fuel at its power
stations at Padiham, Lancs, and Pembroke. The company has asked the
inspectors for more time to reformulate its application.
'We have had constructive discussions with Her Majesty's Inspectorate of
Pollution, and there are quite a few issues outstanding to be considered,'
the company said last night. National Power hopes to burn 3m-4m tonnes of
the fuel a year.
Orimulsion, a bitumen-based fuel imported from Venezuela, has been denounced
by environmentalists as 'the filthy fuel'. The power generation industry
accepts that it contains more sulphur than most oil or coal, but argues that
its overall emissions are less harmful. It is cheaper than domestically
produced coal and competes with imported coal.
PowerGen, the smaller of the two power generators, has been burning
orimulsion for several years on an experimental basis without environmental
controls at two stations in Kent and Cheshire. The fuel acquired some
notoriety last year after an accident at the Kent plant left nearby cars
corroded.
PowerGen burns about 1.5m tonnes a year under permission granted under
earlier pollution control regulations. The company is having to reapply
under the new regulations.
The HMIP did not detail the extra environmental measures it may ask National
Power to take before it will grant permission, but they are expected to
include flue gas desulphurisation equipment.
The stand taken by HMIP was welcomed by the environmental lobby last night.
Mr Chris Smith, Labour's environment spokesman, said: 'For the first time
ever, the government (has) accepted in principle that orimulsion burning
causes damage and that steps must be taken to limit its effect.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
