<HEADLINE>
FT  01 OCT 92 / Move on PSA sell-off expected
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR, Construction Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE SALE of the Property Services Agency's projects division, one of
Britain's biggest construction organisations, is expected to be announced
today by the government.
Tarmac, the country's largest construction and building materials group, is
favourite to take over the division, which designs and constructs buildings
for government and other public-sector bodies.
Many of the division's 2,000 employees are expected to be made redundant.
Construction groups traditionally sub-contract most building work. The
purchaser will also want to merge management teams and make other cost
savings by rationalising the businesses.
The need for any purchaser to fund redundancies and provide guarantees for
work previously completed or undertaken means that the government is
unlikely to raise any cash from the sale.
There have even been suggestions that the government may have to make a cash
payment to the purchaser.
The division, which last year had a turnover of Pounds 190m, has wide
experience of building offices, courts, prisons, laboratories and civil and
military airports.
Its experience of public-sector building requirements and strong links with
government departments has meant that it has continued to win a large share
of public-sector work even though most contracts are now subject to
competitive tender.
About 60 companies originally expressed interest in acquiring the division.
</TEXT>
