yesterday signed an accord with the Offshore Contractors Council covering
about 5,000 engineering and construction workers on North Sea rigs.
It involves setting up a consultative committee to cover health and safety,
security and other issues, but makes no mention of collective bargaining or
representational structures at work.
Workers on platforms before oil production starts have trade union
recognition but that ends when platforms start to produce oil.
