<HEADLINE>
FT  01 OCT 92 / Safety functions may be contracted out
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CATHERINE MILTON, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE government is considering the partial privatisation of the health and
safety inspectorates, according to an internal Health and Safety Executive
document.
The HSE confirmed yesterday that the government had asked advisers to test
the suitability of contracting out HSE regulatory functions.
A programme of market testing in the HSE's internal legal services,
graphics, press, publications and information departments began this year.
Consultants are evaluating cost-effectiveness and the quality of provision.
The new areas to be examined include the seven inspectorates, one of which
is responsible for enforcing safety law at nuclear installations. Together
they are responsible for inspecting hundreds of thousands of workplaces.
Mr John Barrell of the Institute for Occupational Safety and Health, whose
journal Health and Safety Practitioner made the document public, said he did
not think private companies would have the expertise to carry out HSE
inspection and regulation functions.
</TEXT>
