<HEADLINE>
FT  01 OCT 92 / Collor refuses to quit presidency during trial
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTINA LAMB
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRASLIA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT Fernando Collor of Brazil will not resign, his spokesman said
yesterday, despite his crushing defeat in a Congressional vote that opens
the way to an impeachment trial in the Senate.
This would leave Brazil with an acting president and a suspended president
until the conclusion of Mr Collor's trial within the next six months. He is
accused of benefiting from extensive corruption while in office.
In Braslia yesterday, there was discussion over how to transfer power to
Vice-President Itamar Franco after the vote in the House of Representatives
on Tuesday night. He is likely to be declared acting president today.
Mr Franco is preparing an emergency programme, to be announced when he is
confirmed in office. His spokesman said his main concern was a return to
economic growth after three years of recession. The programme would include
tax reform and health and education changes.
Mr Collor's cabinet, incuding economy minister Mr Marclio Marques Moreira,
resigned yesterday, although ministers will stay as caretakers until their
successors are named. The only appointment in view so far is that of Mr
Fernando Henrique Cardoso as foreign minister.
The festivity and excitement which greeted the the impeachment vote has
continued across the country. Street parties went on until dawn and statues
were painted in the national colours of green and yellow to celebrate the
441:38 landslide vote forimpeachment. Demonstrator after demonstrator
proclaimed: 'We're proud to be Brazilians'.
The result of the vote and the formal request for Mr Collor's suspension
from office was handed in the morning by Mr Ibsen Pinheiro, House chairman,
to Mr Mauro Benevides, Senate chairman. The former said the request
contained 'a profound lesson for the whole nation and a clear demonstration
of the strength of our institutions .. We have given the world a lesson in
democracy'.
Mr Collor spent his last day in the presidential palace contemplating the
apparent demise of a political career that seemed promising when he assumed
office in March 1990 as the country's first directly elected president for
30 years, and its youngest.
Aides yesterday described his mood as 'serene', but admitted that he had
reacted furiously to the result of the vote, berating numerous Congressmen
for having 'betrayed' him, and toying with the idea of making an angry
address to the nation.
Mr Etewaldo Dias, his spokesman, said yesterday Mr Collor would collaborate
with the transfer of power, wanting this 'to be civilised and to cause the
minimum possible social agitation'. Mr Dias repeated that there was no
possibility of Mr Collor resigning, but said that he would agree to stand
trial in the Senate.
</TEXT>
