<HEADLINE>
FT  01 OCT 92 / EC close to road tax plan for lorries: Commission proposal
moves Europe closer to single haulage market
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GARDNER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The European Commission yesterday adopted a plan for a mutually agreed
system of road tax discs for EC lorries.
The move is regarded as an essential step for member states to open up their
road haulage markets to each other within the single market due on stream
from January next year.
The plan, announced by Mr Karel van Miert, transport commissioner, is likely
to get approval from the 12, because otherwise individual member states like
Germany are expected to go ahead with national road tax systems likely to
discriminate against outside hauliers.
The Commission's proposal follows a European Court of Justice ruling against
German plans unilaterally to introduce a road tax which foreign lorries
would have to pay. It was put together on Germany's urging.
The measure is scheduled to be decided before the end of the year, to come
into effect in January 1994, and will apply only to motorways and lorries
over 12 tonnes.
The object of the tax is to enable member states to recover infrastructure
costs from their road networks, and also to make railway transport more
attractive. Germany, for instance, has said it plans to use the revenue to
modernise its railways.
But no less important is the now improved prospect of the 12 agreeing to
road cabotage - allowing hauliers from one member state to pick up and
deliver goods inside another member state.
Many countries have blocked opening up the road haulage market for fear that
their own industry would be undercut. Road hauliers in Belgium, for
instance, pay less than a third of the German road tax on a 38-tonne lorry,
and would be correspondingly more competitive if allowed to operate inside
Germany.
National restrictions on outside road hauliers mean that up to a fifth of
European Community lorries are driving around empty at any given time.
The Commission is suggesting an Ecu929 (Pounds 725) a year minimum tax per
40 tonnes of lorry as a reference, but setting no upper limit.
The discs should be easily obtainable, for variable periods of days, weeks
and months, and imply neither discrimination against outside hauliers nor
border checks, Commission officials said. Where, as in France, a toll system
already operates, no change is envisaged.
Officials say governments will be able to reimburse their hauliers for
excessive costs incurred abroad, apparently at French insistence.
Hauliers from poorer peripheral countries such as Greece, Ireland and
Portugal are expected to lose most heavily, because of the distances they
have to travel.
But the final draft of the Commission proposal invokes article 99 of the
Treaty of Rome, covering taxation and requiring unanimity, whereas the
previous intention was to put it through the member states by majority vote,
solely under Article 75 on transport policy.
The possibility of a national veto makes it easier for the poorer countries
to extract concessions.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
