<HEADLINE>
FT  01 OCT 92 / Bribery of BR staff alleged
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH Rail officials were bribed with holidays, lavish meals and trips to
Continental night clubs over a 10-year period to help Plasser Railway
Machinery GB, the rail maintenance suppliers, to win contracts from BR, an
Old Bailey jury was told yesterday.
The widespread bribery was a systematic attempt to corrupt many staff within
BR's civil engineering department. The court was told that far more people
had been involved than the three men on trial.
Plasser Railway Machinery (GB) Ltd, Mr Norbert Jurasek, the company's
managing director, and Mr Michael Brooks, Plasser's company secretary, all
deny nine charges of offering bribes to Mr David Currie, a former head of
BR's civil engineering department, in order to win contracts from BR.
Mr Currie denies nine charges of corruptly accepting the alleged bribes,
which included air tickets from London to South Africa, Chicago and Dublin,
a trip on the Orient Express, a case of champagne and a ticket to watch
rugby at Twickenham.
All three men and the company also deny one charge of conspiring to corrupt
other BR staff.
Opening the case for the prosecution, Mr Michael Worsley QC said the nine
transactions before the court were only 'a mere sample' of the conduct that
took place between 1978 and 1988. A 'mass' of benefits had been offered to
Mr Currie and other people in BR's civil engineering division, he said.
'If there were a charge on the indictment for every transaction of giving
and accepting, the courtroom would be full of defendants and the indictment
would be a mile long,' Mr Worsley told the court.
Mr Jurasek and Mr Brooks were being prosecuted because they were 'at the
heart' of what had happened. Mr Currie was the only BR employee to be
prosecuted, since he had taken more gifts than anyone else and was the most
senior BR employee involved.
Mr Currie received his first gift from Plasser - which depended on BR for 95
per cent of its business - in 1978 when, on a trip to Malaysia, the company
took him out to dinner.
'From that small beginning, the value of the benefits grew,' Mr Worsley
said.
In 1985, Mr Currie became the head of BR's civil engineering department and
benefits to him came in a 'flood'. Plasser paid for Mr Currie to visit
Henley and travel to South Africa and New York. The benefits allowed him to
live the life of a rich man, Mr Worsley said.
Because of the large scale of the benefits from Plasser, the only
interpretation that could be put upon them was that they were corrupt, he
continued. No company would have paid for as much as Plasser had without
expecting something in return.
In Plasser's London offices, a confidential list was kept of who should
receive Christmas presents. Mr Worsley said that Mr Brooks had told his
secretary, a former Metropolitan policewoman: 'These lists are dynamite if
they get into the wrong hands.'
Mr Brooks also told her that Plasser was able to succeed in business only
because of the gifts it provided, Mr Worsley said.
The trial continues today.
</TEXT>
