<HEADLINE>
FT  01 OCT 92 / Modern art depressed: Saleroom
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONY THORNCROFT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SOTHEBY'S sale yesterday of medium-quality British and Irish modern pictures
offered a good snapshot of the state of the contemporary art market. It was
predictably depressing, with a total of Pounds 332,362 and 44 per cent
unsold.
Ms Susie Pollen, expert in charge, said the auction confirmed that demand is
patchy and unpredictable. Dealers have virtually disappeared as buyers and
the taste of private collectors is variable.
Irish paintings did best, with The Red Table by Colin Middleton beating its
estimate at Pounds 10,285 and Winter in Galway by Jack Butler Yeats selling
within forecast at Pounds 9,922. A typical marine picture by Edward Seago
made Pounds 10,285, the bottom of its estimate. Dull pictures and modern
abstracts were particularly ignored, although the trend was bucked by
Untitled 1960, by Adrian Heath, which did well at Pounds 9,317.
Even in a depressed antiques market, exceptional items still sell. A Thomas
Tompion ebony miniature striking bracket clock from the early 1690s sold at
Christie's yesterday for Pounds 85,800, within estimate. In 1951 Christie's
had auctioned it for 1,800 guineas.
A similar Tompion clock reflected the caution in the market by selling for
Pounds 49,400, below forecast. It had belonged to the celebrated furniture
collector Geoffrey Blackwell. A walnut bracket timepiece by Joseph Knibb
from the Blackwell collection was just above target at Pounds 35,200.
The surprise of the session, which totalled Pounds 441,000 with 11 per cent
unsold, was a silver-cased perpetual calendar astronomical carriage
timepiece made in 1897 by Joseph Jump. It sold for Pounds 52,800, around
twice its estimate.
Christie's Swire had a disappointment at its Hong Kong sale of Chinese art
when the top lot, an important wood sculpture of the Buddhist Goddess of
Mercy, carved in the 12th century AD, was unsold at HKDollars 7.5m (Pounds
530,000).
</TEXT>
